        <div class="text">Bob Marley was born on February 6, 1945, in Nine Mile, Jamaica. e faced challenges growing up, including racial and economic difficulties. His father was a British naval officer, and his mother was a Jamaican woman. Marley started his music career in the early 1960s, initially forming a group called The Wailers with Bunny Wailer and Peter Tosh.His music often addressed social and political issues, promoting peace, love, and unity. Songs like "One Love" and "Get Up, Stand Up" reflect these themes. Some of his most famous albums include "Catch a Fire," "Rastaman Vibration," and "Exodus." His posthumous album, "Legend," remains hugely popular.Marley's music continues to inspire artists and activists. He is often regarded as one of the greatest musicians of all time.Marley was diagnosed with melanoma in 1977. He continued to perform until his health declined. He passed away on May 11, 1981, at the age of 36.


           
            
